answers.body_markdown:
After removing one item, the call of `notify` in the consumer *does not* cause the producer to continue executing immediately because the consumer is still holding the lock of the monitor. It is not until the consumer `wait`s, that it relinquishes the monitor lock, and the producer can acquire it. 

Of course, the consumer can also relinquish the lock by exiting the `synchronized` block, but that&#39;s never going to happen :)

See the documentation for [`notify`][1]:

&gt; Wakes up a single thread that is waiting on this object&#39;s monitor. [...]
&gt;
&gt; The awakened thread will not be able to proceed until the current thread relinquishes the lock on this object. 

Therefore, the consumer consumes everything, then `wait`s, and that&#39;s when the producer starts running. And the same situation happens again, in the producer thread. The producer does not give up the lock, until the upper limit is reached and it `wait`s.

One way to achieve &quot;consumers consumes one item and then the producer starts producing another&quot; is, in the consumer, to put the synchronised block outside the infinite loop, and `sleep` outside the synchronised block. This gives the produce a chance to acquire the lock and add items.


    public void consumer() throws InterruptedException {
        while (true) {
            synchronized(lock) {
                if (list.size() == LOWER_LIMIT) {
                    System.out.println(&quot;Waiting for adding items...&quot;);
                    lock.wait();
                } else {
                    System.out.println(&quot;Removing: &quot; + list.remove(list.size() - 1));
                    lock.notify();
                }
            }
            Thread.sleep(1000);
        }
    }

