answers.body_markdown:
You can build an Annotation Processor (AP). This has a ton of warts, so let me first expand on those before you commit to doing this:

* You have to save the file that defines the regex, run the build, and only then can you _use_ the regex you designed. Vs. e.g. adding a method someplace, and then switching to another source file, where you can use it immediately. (As in, the IDE knows its there). Eclipse in particular does have internal AP support and can run them on its own after you save the file, but this is tricky in different manners.
* Because the AP needs to be run by IDEs _and_ build tools, the version of java you compile your AP with is tricky.
* Error reporting of APs running in IDEs isn&#39;t great.
* Testing APs is notoriously hard.
* The AP API is not exactly simple.
* Trying to manage the results of incremental compilation is difficult. Either you do it (high learning curve), or you leave it out, which is at least an option here, but it does mean that _deleting_ a regex definining source file _does not_ remove the actual regex engine class that the AP made.
* Different runners (`javac`, `ecj`, eclipse (and therefore, VSCode because it uses eclipse as a language server for java), intellij, and so on) implement the AP API in slightly different ways. You have to test on all of it. At least javac and eclipse if you want the support to be good).
* Generally the AP itself has to be an entirely separate project.

If you&#39;re okay with all of that, the end result once you&#39;ve written this AP is that you write something like:

```java
@Regexify(&quot;(?&lt;left&gt;\d+) + (?&lt;right&gt;\d+)&quot;)
public interface MyRegexDef {}
```

and compile it. The result of doing this (because your AP processor can see that and take steps accordingly), is that this class just &#39;appears&#39; (you don&#39;t write it - your AP generated it, it just starts existing after one compilation run):

```java
// Generated by AP
public final class MyRegex {
  private static final Pattern PATTERN = Pattern.compile(&quot;(?&lt;left&gt;\d+) + (?&lt;right&gt;\d+)&quot;);

  public static final List&lt;MyRegex&gt; find(String in) {
    var m = PATTERN.matcher(in);
    var out = new ArrayList&lt;MyRegex&gt;();
    while (m.find()) {
      out.add(m.group(&quot;left&quot;), m.group(&quot;right&quot;));
null;
    }
    return out;
  }

  public static final MyRegex match(String in) {
    var m = PATTERN.matcher(in);
    return m.matches() ? new MyRegex(m.group(&quot;left&quot;, m.group(&quot;right&quot;)) : null;
  }

  private final String left;
  private final String right;

  public String getLeft() { return left; }
  public String getRight() { return left; }

  @Override public boolean equals(Object other) {
    if (other == null || other.getClass() != MyRegex.class) return false;
    return ((MyRegex) other).left.equals(left) &amp;&amp; ((MyRegex) other).right.equals(right);
    // really should also check null v null
  }

  @Override public int hashCode() {
    return left.hashCode() * 31 + right.hashCode();
    // deal with nulls better
  }

  @Override public String toString() {
    return &quot;MyRegex[Left: &quot; + left + &quot; Right: &quot; + right + &quot;]&quot;;
  }

  private MyRegex(String left, String right) {
    this.left = left;
    this.right = right;
  }
}

// you get the idea - you can make this look however you want it to look.
```

in addition if the regex is e.g. invalid (mismatched `(` for example), you&#39;d get a _write time_ error, as in, a red wavy underline would appear under the regex string in `MyRegexDef` and the `MyRegex` file is not generated at all.

If this sounds like what you want - writing a complete AP tutorial is beyond the scope of SO, but the above outlays what would happen if you spent the time to learn how that works.

